<KurlandJun44DeBr> <As a consequence of the collapse of Army Group Centre following the Operation Bagration offensive that started on 22nd June 1944 the Soviets have reached the Baltic States. The developments of the last weeks of July means that there is a serious risk that Army Group North will be cut off. Luftflotte 1 is desperately trying to delay the enemy advance and relieve the pressure on our hard-pressed infantry.> 
<KurlandJun44DeDb> <A determined drive by the Soviet 2nd Baltic Front has reached the coast west of Riga and separated Army Groups North and Centre. Unless Army Group North can withdraw in good order and rejoin the rest of the German army we risk a greater catastrophe than Stalingrad.>

<KurlandAug44DeBr> <The Soviet summer offensive has bogged down - but only because their amazing success has stretched their supply  lines to breaking point. In our sector the Russians have broken through between Army Groups North and Centre and catastrophe threatens. Our 3rd Panzer Army has been ordered to attack in the Tukkum area and retake Mitau in conjunction with a withdrawal westwards by Army Group North. We need to ensure the link-up of our forces at all costs if we are not to leave hundreds of thousands of men behind.>
<KurlandAug44DeDb> <We have re-established a link to Army Group North, though we couldnt retake Mitau. Now we need to stabilise the front line - it is collapsing everywhere else. The Rumanians have just changed sides after a new Russian offensive in the south and the Americans and Canadians have trapped huge numbers of our troops in the Falaise pocket.>

<KurlandOct44DeBr> <Just as we stabilise one part of the front line, news comes of a major Soviet troop build-up stretching from Mitau as far south as Kauen. It seems we can expect another Soviet broad front offensive: they can be everywhere - we cannot. The Bauske area is particularly threatened, with one of our divisions facing two enemy corps. In addition it is vital we hold Riga - a Russian breakthrough here would give them a valuable naval base from which their torpedo boats and submarines could threaten the supply ships that keep Army Group North alive.>
<KurlandOct44DeDb> <In just five days the Soviet 1st Baltic Front broke through to the Baltic Sea coast near Polangen. There was nothing we could do. We have, however, kept the Riga corridor open and Army Group North have withdrawn in good order into the Kurland peninsula and established a defensive perimeter in accordance with Hitlers orders. Memel has been surrounded and is under terrible pressure and further south Soviet forces have set foot on German territory for the first time, unleashing tides of refugees.>

<KurlandNov44DeBr> <The last months have seen a massive loss of men, material and territory. Army Group North is restricted to a small area and is bunkered down - our mobile reserves are so limited that there can be no thought of a break-out to re-establish links with Army Group Centre, themselves under enormous pressure. As AG Centre withdraws, Army Group North has been ordered to tie down as many Soviet divisions as possible. Comparisons with the Sixth Armys position at Stalingrad are unavoidable, though our control of the Baltic Sea offers a reliable supply line that they did not have. Reports are coming in of a Soviet offensive against the southern defences of the Kurland cauldron. Things are hotting up again.>
<KurlandNov44DeDb> <The Soviet 1st and 2nd Baltic Fronts were thrown back with heavy losses to both sides. We can hope for a breathing space on the ground, perhaps, but Russian air attacks remain as intense as ever. Our fuel is beginning to run low and is limiting our ability to provide cover. Army Group North is down to half a million men with little prospect of replacing lost tanks, artillery and vehicles.>

<KurlandDec44DeBr> <The pressure on our defences is growing again - it looks like there will be another attempt to crush us before Christmas. Army Group Centre reports that the enemy are now firmly entrenched inside East Prussia while Army Group Kurland report heavy attacks on our lifelines - the ports of Libau and Windau. Now the emphasis seems to have switched to intense artillery and aerial preparation of our front lines so we can expect action today.>
<KurlandDec44DeDb> <The Soviet offensive lasted until the last day of 1944 and has cost us heavily, though our lines remained unbroken. As well as the hundreds of thousands in the Kurland pocket, our troops are also still just holding out in Memel, where the situation is grave. That JG54 scored its 9000th kill is remarkable, but seems unlikely to be enough.>

<KurlandJan45DeBr> <The great Soviet winter offensive has driven westwards - Knigsberg is isolated and  Silesia  invaded. Both the Kurland and Memel pockets are once again the subjects of intense attack. High command are pulling men out to throw into the main battle in the Reich - but we must hold on!>
<KurlandJan45DeDb> <We have held the front in Kurland but we have lost control of the airfields at Cranz north of Knigsberg  and the Red Army have taken Memel. In the Reich the Red Army stands on the Oder River just 150km from Berlin while in the west the Anglo-American forces have crossed the Rhine - things are serious.>

<KurlandFeb45DeBr> <The loss of the airbases in the Knigsberg pocket to our south mean that Luftflotte 1 must carry the entire burden of the air war here on the Baltic. This morning, 20th February 1945, we woke to the news that our lines are once more under attack but are holding, so far. Our most potent offensive forces have been withdrawn to Germany, so it will now just be a bitter defence to the end. All thoughts of breakout or counter-attack seem to have vanished.>
<KurlandFeb45DeDb> <Another battle - losses on both sides have been heavy, but the enemy can sustain them better than we can. Our situation grows worse and worse, especially where fuel is concerned. Our ability to operate and resist is becoming seriously limited. On the other hand the Russians seem if anything slightly less aggressive than before, as if they know we are stuck here and can safely be contained until Berlin falls.>

<KurlandMar45DeBr> <After a mere weeks peace the next offensive is upon us, with intense air and artillery preparation. Our defences are weak but defend we must. General Pflugbeil has released stocks of aviation fuel to ensure we can provide the cover our hard-pressed infantry need. It's time to hunt still more Sturmoviks.>
<KurlandMar45DeDb> <The Red Army has made inroads into our positions between Frauenburg and Tukkum but failed to achieve the decisive breakthrough they had been hoping for. Our lines are battered but they are holding, although in places it was only the direct fire of our artillery that held things together.>

<KurlandApr45DeBr> <The Wehrmacht has crumbled everywhere but here - our lines stand firm and we remain a thorn in the side of the Soviet advance on Berlin. Let us do what we can to relieve the pressure on our homeland. The parlous fuel situation means it will be precious little but we will fight as best we can.>
<KurlandApr45DeDb> <The Russian storm broke on Berlin less than a month ago. Hitler is dead and Admiral Dnitz has surrendered - the guns have finally fallen silent. The troops of Army Group Kurland are marching into captivity, but we pilots have been ordered to fly out to Schleswig-Holstein and safety, taking as many of our ground crew as we can cram into the fuselage. The fight is over - lets get out of here!>

<KurlandJun44RuBr> <Operation Bagration has driven the Germans back across Belarus and into Poland, opening up weaknesses where the German 16th and 18th Armies meet. Our 2nd and 3rd Baltic Fronts are driving into this gap and the 1st Baltic Front has already taken Schaulen. The aim is to thrust through Mitau and Tukkum to reach the Baltic coast west of Riga and cut off the entire German Army Group North based around Riga and Tallinn. Further south we aim to strike towards the borders of East Prussia and so set foot on Germany proper for the first time. The 15th Air Army is tasked with supporting both of these efforts.>
<KurlandJun44RuDb> <Our advance in the north has been hugely successful and our forces have reached the coast, although not in strength. We can expect a German counter-attack imminently and our Sturmoviks and bombers will have to make up for a lack of tanks and prepared defences in this sector by blunting the German spearheads. In the south we have occupied large areas of Latvia and Lithuania but haven't had the breakthrough we were aiming for. Nevertheless, the encirclement of the whole of Army Group North means that the Germans in the south will have to decide between counter-attacking our forces in the north or providing a determined defence of East Prussia.>

<KurlandAug44RuBr> <We have finally expelled the hated invader from Russia after three long years! Now the frontline runs along the borders of the Reich itself as we approach East Prussia.  In the north our reconnaissance shows a massive build-up of enemy forces east and west of our corridor to the Baltic: our bombers and sturmoviks are on stand-by to attack the moment the Germans break cover. We are in a strong position, but faced by the veterans of JG54 and JG51 we must stay alert!>
<KurlandAug44RuDb> <The German counter-attack was heavier than expected and broke through our lines to re-establish contact between the enemy's Army Groups Centre and North, albeit along a tenuous strip along the coast. The Germans are clearly stronger than we thought and remain in firm control of Riga. It is time for us to pause and collect our strength after the summer's headlong rush.>

<KurlandOct44RuBr> <Our Divisions stand on the borders of the Reich and are poised for a massive onslaught on the German positions. New supplies of tanks and assault guns backed by huge stockpiles of artillery ammunition mean that our huge push is imminent. The strategy is two-fold - a direct attack on Riga and a westwards thrust towards Memel. The Memel attack is once again aimed at the juncture of the German Army Groups North and Centre and a perceived weakness in their defences.>
<KurlandOct44RuDb> <Success! The 1st Baltic Front reached the coast north of Memel in a few days, followed by the 3rd Belorussian Front reaching the coast south of Memel 48 hours later. A massive rift has opened in German lines and our tank and assault divisions are pouring in. Defences are being thrown up on each side of the corridor to hinder German counter-attacks and Memel is besieged. Our attack on Riga was less successful - the city was finally taken but only after the Germans had successfully withdrawn westwards. Still, the German Army Group North is now trapped on the Kurland peninsula with hundreds of thousands of men relying on air and sea supply.>

<KurlandNov44RuBr> <The Red Army is once more on the attack - into East Prussia in the south and towards the vital German-held port of Libau in the north. The Air Force has been tasked with attacks on enemy ports and shipping in the enemy's rear and the destruction of enemy tanks, self-propelled guns and "88's at the front. Our fighter regiments have been ordered to shape up - losses of IL-2's and Pe-2's in particular have been too high. A number of elite La-5FN, La-7 and Yak-3 Regiments have been sent to our front to conduct free hunts and fighter sweeps and  take on the German fighter units.>
<KurlandNov44RuDb> <It is clear that the German pocket in the Kurland peninsula is not about to collapse. Our attacks have reached none of their goals and have met with such determined resistance on the ground and in the air that we will need to pause before deciding what to do next. In spite of the numerical superiority of our 15th Air Army, the German Luftflotte 1 is scoring disproportionately highly.>

<KurlandDec44RuBr> <Stalin has ordered the destruction of the German forces in the Kurland pocket by the end of the year so that the forces of the Baltic Fronts can be diverted southwards to the fight for Poland and the push for Berlin. That leaves us 10 days to take Libau and Windau and thereby cut the German lifelines across the sea.>
<KurlandDec44RuDb> <Our attacks have rarely penetrated more than a few hundred metres and at terrible cost. We have reached the end of 1944 no closer to the destruction of the Kurland Pocket than we were at the end of October. Our aircraft losses have been terrible, particularly around Libau, and for very little effect on the enemy's supply operations. Even besieged Memel is holding out under terrific bombardment and in the south we have not made to progress we anticipated.>

<KurlandJan45RuBr> <The Germans appear to have gone over to a purely defensive stance, having withdrawn most of their armour for a counter-offensive on their western front and in the hope of reducing the fuel and supply problems. It seems they are not anticipating an attack in the cold and wet January weather.>
<KurlandJan45RuDb> <We have lost over 200 aircraft for very little progress on the ground. Stalin is furious and Goebells overjoyed. We have been given a week to resupply then we attack again. This cannot be allowed to continue! The only good news comes from the south of our sector, where Memel has finally fallen and our forces stand at the gates of Koenigsberg.>

<KurlandFeb45RuBr> <Thanks to the rapid advance of our forces through Poland, the Red Army stands at the gates of Germany itself. The remaining enemy forces in East Prussia have been bottled up around Koenigsberg, Memel has fallen and the time has come to renew our pressure on Kurland. Our Airforce  is once again called on to go all out, especially as many of our best ground units have already been diverted westwards for the final push on Berlin. Still, it seems that the Germans are running low on fuel and air opposition may be diminishing, although the flak is as intensive as ever. That will be a major problem around Libau, especially for the Bostons of the Baltic Fleet Airforce that have been tasked with shutting the port down.>
<KurlandFeb45RuDb> <The German defence is just as tenacious as ever and in spite of some successes it is proving impossible to drive the enemy back. The enemy 190's are proving as deadly as ever in spite of the numbers we knock down.>

<KurlandMar45RuBr> <We are facing exhausted troops with little in the way of fuel and ammunition. The quality of their pilots is dropping as their experts are shot down one by one. Stalin wants the Kurland pocket eliminated by the time Berlin falls - there is not to be a "last stand" anywhere in the east. A vast array of B-25's, Bostons, IL-4's, Pe-2's and Sturmoviks has been gathered to pummel the defenders into submission.>
<KurlandMar45RuDb> <Our High Command have called a halt to this senseless battle of attrition. With all eyes on our forces preparing for the onslaught on Berlin it has been decided to concentrate on strangling the Kurland supply lines with naval aircraft, submarines and torpedo boats. We have already lost too many men for too little reward.>

<KurlandApr45RuBr> <The end is fast approaching. The final push into the enemy capital is about to begin. Our task is to pressure the Kurland pocket and prevent the enemy using ships and aircraft to transfer his troops westwards. We will do this not only by attacks on his supply lines but also by increasing pressure at the front and making it impossible for him to withdraw units.>
<KurlandApr45RuDb> <Victory! Hitler is dead, Germany is conquered! In Latvia alone over 250,000 men have laid down their arms and surrendered, in spite of a huge effort by the German Navy to take off as many men as they could. The war is over - let us rejoice!>

<Murmansk4ARuBr> <The Germans have been massing around Kirkenes in northern Norway and on the 22nd June they crossed the border into northern Finland,occupying the Petsamo area. This puts them within easy striking range of Murmansk. Our ice-free gateway to the northern seas and the Northern Fleet itself are at risk. Nor is Murmansk the only target - if the enemy can cut the railway to the south then Murmansk will starve. The units of the 14th Air Army and the Northern Fleet Airforce have outdated aircraft - High Command have assessed the situation and new aircraft including cannon-armed Polikapov I-16's and the latest MiG-3's and LaGG-3's will arrive in less than a month. But that gives the enemy some three weeks to cover the short distance from the Finnish border. We have two advantages: in contrast to the disasters further south in Poland and the Ukraine, effective aircraft dispersal and poor weather on the 22nd itself have meant that very few of our aircraft were lost in the initial German strikes. Secondly, our pilots are among the most experienced of all Soviet aviators. Many have fought in the Winter War and against the Japanese and are older than average. We need to hold out until we can get reinforcements from the south. In addition, there is already talk of alliance with Britain and Murmansk will be a key part of any proposed military cooperation.>
<Murmansk4ARuDb> <We have taken many casualties and had to give up vital ground, but all is not lost! Last night LaGG-3 and model 24 I-16's were flown in from Monchegorsk. The British have flown in Hurricanes from a naval unit offshore and more are being assembled near Archangelsk. It is time to avenge our fallen comrades!>

<Murmansk41RuBr> <The Germans have swept over the border from Finland but are finding it much harder going than they expected. They seem to have split their forces in two - one group headed directly for Murmansk, the other attempting to cut the railway lines further south. If either succeeds, we are lost. British convoys have started arriving, bringing much needed supplies, including modern Hurricane fighters and pilots and engineers who will help us get them into service. 2 GSAP of the Northern Fleet have received a squadron of MiG-3's and some Pe-2 bombers while the 14th Air Army have got LaGG-3's. Cannon-armed I-16's have started knocking down enemy Stukas and there is a growing sense of confidence in our forces. The enemy may be hurting us but we are certainly hurting them! Our mission is to protect Murmansk and the British convoys.>
<Murmansk41RuDb> <It is now dark for 22 hours a day and the intense polar cold has grounded all flying. The British squadrons returned home at the end of November, leaving us hundreds of aircraft, with more arriving every month. Our forces have been battered and stretched beyond belief and many of our most experienced pilots have died, but still we fight one. We will see what 1942 has in store when flying resumes at the beginning of February.>

<Murmansk42RuBr> <In spite of the heroic efforts of all our comrades, the Germans remain within striking distance of Murmansk. The British have been sending us P-40 fighters that are gradually filling up our Naval airforce regiments and now that the USA is in the war it seems we have been promised plenty more. Furthermore, after the danger to Moscow receeded in January with our successful counter-attacks we have started getting PVO units to help protect Murmansk from enemy bombing. We have also converted 120 Hurricanes to carry bombs, as the famous IL-2 Sturmovik is required for the central combat zones to the south. To counter our growing strength, the Germans are switching tactics. Rather than attacking Murmansk directly they are attacking the British and US convoys with a new Gruppe of He-111 torpedo bombers, I/KG26, who have been training in Italy. Together with Ju-88 dive bombers they represent a real threat to our lifeline from the West. Meanwhile Bf-110's and Ju-88's are hitting the railway to the heartlands as quickly as we can repair it. However it seems our successes last year have at least driven the ageing Ju-87 Stuka out of the northern skies!>
<Murmansk42RuDb> <The war in the north seems to have bogged down into stalemate. The Germans cannot dislodge us from Murmansk and have contented themselves with disrupting our supply chain by attacking convoys and the railway. For our part we seem unable to mass sufficient reserves to push the Germans back out of northern Finland; the thousands of trucks, jeeps, tanks, radios and the tonnes of other supplies are mostly going to feed the bitter struggle west of Moscow. Good news though - the German Sixth Army has been surrounded in Stalingrad and news comes of a major push by our forces west of Moscow.>

<Murmansk43RuBr> <After the shock of seeing the latest German fighters like the Messerschmitt Bf-109F and the Focke-Wulf 190A3 tear through our regiments last year, it seems we are finally achieving parity in terms of equipment. Our fighter regiments have received the P-39 Airacobra and later versions of the P-40. The Yaks and Lavochkins are reaching comparable quality and the latest IL-2's with rear gunner seats and modern munitions are filling our attack regiments. The incomparable Boston is replacing the slower Hampden and IL-4 in our bomber regiments and after the success of the great Stalingrad encirclement battle it seems the Germans are now on the back foot. We must not be complacent though - the Messerschmitt model G has appeared in the North and the German flak is deadlier than ever.>
<Murmansk43RuDb> <This year has been hard. The loss of so many of our comrades for so little change on the ground is a terrible blow. But while we have held our positions here, the Germans have lost thousands of tanks at Kursk and have been driven out of the Kuban, while their front now stands hundreds of kilometres from the gates of Moscow. And it is due in no small part to our efforts here. And we have been assured that next year will see a great strategic offensive!>

<Murmansk44RuBr> <You have just returned to the North after a well-earned period of relative calm instructing at the flying school in Lipetsk. That sunshine must have been terrible - I'm sure you're glad to be back in the ice and cold. You are just in time for the big push west - the Petsamo-Kirkenes operation. Our forces have advanced into the Karelian Isthmus and knocked Finland out of the war, which together with a strategic realignment by Sweden has left German forces in the North quite isolated. British and Norwegian units flying out of Scotland are harrying German sea supply traffic and reports from German prisoners speak of low fuel and ammunition stocks. It is time to advance and seize the moment. The main danger will come from the fighter and Jabo units of Gefechtsverband Kuhlmey, a large part of which decamped into our area of operations after the Finnish ceasefire in the South. We need to prevent them hitting our army and its chain of supply as we advance.>
<Murmansk44RuDb> <Victory! For the second time in five years we have occupied northern Finland after a hard-fought campaign - and this time we are not about to hand it back. The Petsamo region and its nickel mines will remain ours. American airforce units secretly based in northern Sweden have begun ferrying Norwegian armed policemen into what remains of Kirkenes. Our troops will withdraw as soon as the Norwegians feel they have things under control. The German troops who were threatening Murmansk so recently are retreating in disorder down the spine of Norway.>

<Murmansk4ADeBr> <Gentlemen, welcome! The bad weather of the last few days is breaking up and it is time to attack. Unfortunately we have lost the element of surprise that has seen the Russian airforce devastated in the central sectors. Still, no matter - we are opposed only by older Polikarpov fighters here and a few of the so-called "fast bombers" that are no match for our Messerschmitts. Our hardy mountain troops have occupied Northern Finland with our ally's agreement and last night began crossing the Russian border. Murmansk is close!>
<Murmansk4ADeDb> <Our troops have advanced, but not as we had hoped. The Russian resistance has been fiercer than expected and the Russian fliers have committed themselves with a bravery and skill we had not anticipated. This kind of low altitude skirmishing is something new for us but we will have to adapt! More bad news: reconnaissance of Russian bases has revealed the presence of more modern fighters and bombers like the MiG-3, LaGG-3 and Pe-2. In addition a British convoy has been spotted north of Murmansk.>

<Murmansk41DeBr> <The High Command, frustrated by the slow progress of our army towards Murmansk, has cancelled the southern push to cut the Kirov Railroad and has put all our assets in the north with the aim of being in Murmansk before the weather closes in. The air war in the north is about to intensify. LaGG-3 aircraft yesterday intercepted Stukas over Ristikent and British Hurricanes have been spotted near Murmansk, presumably on orientation flights. Whether the pilots are British or Russian has yet to be determined. The time has come for an all-out effort to bomb a way clear for our attacking divisions and to prevent the Soviet airmen from stalling our advance.>
<Murmansk41DeDb> <In spite of the huge number of enemy aircraft shot down by our fighters and the devastation wrought by our Stukas and bombers, we have still not decisively routed the Soviets. The British convoys have supplied the enemy with hundreds of fighters and the presence of newer Russian types has made us wary of committing unescorted aircraft. The Stuka is to be withdrawn from the north - we have simply lost too many. We need to refit over the winter and see what 1942 will bring.>

<Murmansk42DeBr> <Last year we almost reached Murmansk but we ran out of supplies and momentum and had to withdraw a little as winter closed in. Now the weather has opened up again it is time to maintain pressure on the enemy. A special factor now is the large amount of British and US convoys making for Murmansk and Archangelsk - the Ju-88's and He-111's are finding it harder and harder to attack them and will need escorting. For the fighter pilots things look good: we have sent our old Messerschmitt Bf 109E-4s back to the Navy and we have late-model Emils and are getting the newer Bf-109F's in the fighter Gruppen and even some Fw-190A models as fast strike aircraft. The enemy has nothing that can match us!>
<Murmansk42DeDb> <As 1942 draws to a close, we have experienced neither the early rapid advances of German units further south, nor their later collapse. The front line has remained stable, success and failure measured more in terms of our interdiction of the enemy's supply chain. We have had our successes but too much is still getting through.>

<Murmansk43DeBr> <The advantages we had in 1942 are eroding fast: the new Bf109G in our fighter regiments no longer stands head and shoulders above the enemy, now that they have received large numbers of the American Airacobra. Their Yak and Lavochkin fighters are also of better quality and are available in greater numbers, while their newer IL-2's with rear gunner are harder targets. The quality of their pilots in this sector is getting better all the time. But fight we must: American ships are bringing aluminium, bombers and tanks to the enemy. The British carry fighters, jeeps and radios. If we cannot sink their ships we have to hit the railways that carry these supplies to the interior. And then there are the steadily increasing numbers of Russian troops, tanks, trucks and artillery massed against us. We will need repeated attacks to disrupt any thoughts they may have of attacking us.>
<Murmansk43DeDb> <This year has been hard. The loss of so many of our comrades for so little change on the ground is a terrible blow. And while we have held our positions here, our units have lost thousands of tanks at Kursk and have been driven out of the Kuban, while our panzers now stand hundreds of kilometres from the gates of Moscow. There seems to be little prospect of a quick reversal in our fortunes.>

<Murmansk44DeBr> <Information from Russian prisoners suggests that a major offensive is about to be lauched against us. Our aerial reconnaissance would appear to confirm this - large numbers of IL-2 Sturmoviks have been concentrated on airbases near the front. Our situation is serious - the Finnish ceasefire and the Swedish strategic realignment have left us isolated, reduced to getting supplies up the long Norwegian coast in vulnerable freighters under constant attack from British and Norwegian units flying out of Scotland. However in some ways we are stronger than last year - elements of Gefechtsverband Kuhlmey including new Fw-190F8 attack aircraft and new models of the Fw-190 and Bf-109G have joined us here in the north. Whether that is enough to make a difference is up to you!>
<Murmansk44DeDb> <The Russian onslaught was overwhelming. We seriously underestimated their resources and the concentrations of force they could employ. In light of our isolation and poor supply state it was all we could do to retreat in good order. The north belongs to the Russians.>

<MurmanskR41RuBr> <The Germans have swept over the border from Finland but are finding it much harder going than they expected. They seem to have split their forces in two - one group headed directly for Murmansk, the other attempting to cut the railway lines further south. If either succeeds, we are lost. British convoys have started arriving, bringing much needed supplies, including modern Hurricane fighters and pilots and engineers who will help us get them into service. 2 GSAP of the Northern Fleet have received a squadron of MiG-3's and some Pe-2 bombers while the 14th Air Army have got LaGG-3's. Cannon-armed I-16's have started knocking down enemy Stukas and there is a growing sense of confidence in our forces. The enemy may be hurting us but we are certainly hurting them! Our mission is to establish German positions for our artillery and bombers to attack.>
<MurmanskR41RuDb> <It is now dark for 22 hours a day and the intense polar cold has grounded all flying. The British squadrons returned home at the end of November, leaving us hundreds of aircraft, with more arriving every month. Our forces have been battered and stretched beyond belief and many of our most experienced pilots have died, but still we fight one. We will see what 1942 has in store when flying resumes at the beginning of February.>

<MurmanskR44RuBr> <With the Finns out of the war the time has come to drive the isolated Germans out of northern Finland and Norway. You are just in time for the big push west - the Petsamo-Kirkenes operation. It is time to advance and seize the moment, but we can only do that based on a good appreciation of the enemy positions and ship movements. Your reconnaissance flight is a vital part of the operation. Good luck.>
<MurmanskR44RuDb> <Victory! For the second time in five years we have occupied northern Finland after a hard-fought campaign - and this time we are not about to hand it back. The Petsamo region and its nickel mines will remain ours. American airforce units secretly based in northern Sweden have begun ferrying Norwegian armed policemen into what remains of Kirkenes. Our troops will withdraw as soon as the Norwegians feel they have things under control. The German troops who were threatening Murmansk so recently are retreating in disorder down the spine of Norway.>


<MurmanskS42DeBr> <Last year we almost reached Murmansk but we ran out of supplies and momentum and had to withdraw a little as winter closed in. Now the weather has opened up again it is time to maintain pressure on the enemy. A special factor now is the large amount of British and US convoys making for Murmansk and Archangelsk - Germany's first torpedo attack unit, I/KG26 has been sent to Kirkenes after training in Italy. We will sink the Allied shipping!>
<MurmanskS42DeDb> <As 1942 draws to a close, we have experienced neither the early rapid advances of German units further south, nor their later collapse. The front line has remained stable, success and failure measured more in terms of our interdiction of the enemy's supply chain. We have had our successes but too much is still getting through.>


<KBFBaltic41RuBr> <The Germans have broken through our defences around Riga, capturing the city within the first two weeks of the war. Now they hold Tallinn and they are pressing forward towards the borders of Mother Russia herself! Leningrad lies within their reach, with the Finns already closing on the city from the north. The Germans have momentarily slowed their advance, with their tanks waiting for the infantry and supplies to catch up. Now is the moment to throw what we have at them. Unfortunately our resources are low. The Germans destroyed almost our entire Army air force in the area at Libava and Kaunas. Now the air force of the Baltic Fleet is to be thrown into their path. Our Regiment has modern MiG-3's to combat their aircraft and older I-16 and I-153 fighters to strafe and bomb their positions. Pilot - uphold the glory of the Navy and the Red Banner of the Revolution.>
<KBFBaltic41RuDb> <We fought gloriously against the invader but our Regiment has few planes remaining and the Panzers are rolling again. We have been ordered to fall back towards Leningrad. You are to be sent ahead by train with the 3rd Eskadrilya to pick up new and better fighters at Oranienbaum.>

<GOF41WinterDeBr> <As of Nov 1, 1941 Army Group North and the Finnish I and IV Korps have almost completely surrounded Leningrad. Just to the east we are closing on Tikhvin which is a main rail center supporting Leningrad. We have been unable to penetrate the city's main defences, but have effectively blockaded it. When Moscow is taken, those troops will help in the final assault against the city./n/nWith the Ladogasee freezing, the Bolsheviks will try to supply the city over the frozen lake. We must take every step to keep the "Eisbahn" closed and to keep up pressure all along the northern front. Bf-109F4s of JG54 "Green Hearts", based at Siverskaya, will sweep the skies of enemy aircraft. The Ju-87's of the Stukageschwadern and our level bombers from KG1 and KG4 will annihilate the enemy on the ground and the Red Banner Baltic Fleet at their "safe" anchorage in Leningrad.>

<GOF41WinterRuBr> <As of Nov 1, 1941 The Germans and their Finnish allies have nearly surrounded Leningrad. The only routes open are over the frozen surface of Lake Ladoga. Sorties conducted by the VVS-KBF in the coming weeks will be largely in support of the Ice Road. We must keep these routes open and the supply trains safe. Our armies are reinforcing to push the Fascists out of Shlisselburg and open up the land route to Leningrad. Mobile naval units of the KBF are at anchor under heavy flak protection in the Neva River, but may also need our protection. Our Sturmovik units will continue to hit the enemy wherever he is. Millions of our Comrades in Lenin's City are counting on us!>

<GOF41WinterFiBr> <As of Nov 1, 1941 We have pushed the Russians nearly back to the gates of Leningrad itself. We must keep up the pressure if we are to ensure a future free of Soviet aggression. The extreme skill and spirits of our flyers has so far given us the edge in combat against the Russians. The B-239 and G.50 are competitive with anything on the enemy side. We will continue our tempo of air operations in support of our army and to cut off Leningrad from resupply across the frozen surface of Lake Ladoga.>

<GOF41WinterDeDb> <As of Feb 28, 1942 we have kept up our pressure on Leningrad but the city still stands, the stubborn Bolsheviks would rather starve than surrender. Moscow has not yet been taken so we will have to wait indefinitely for reinforcements from Army Group Center. We have had to retreat from Tikhvin but still hold Shlisselburg. With winter nearing an end, Ladogasee will thaw and Leningrad will become an island, and the Ladogasee will become a watery tomb for any ships or barges trying to cross.>

<GOF41WinterRuDb> <As of Feb 28, 1942 the Germans have failed to take Leningrad, but we are still under siege and a terrible famine has continued in the city. We must hope the supply situation gets better in the spring when new offensives can open more supply routes. We have driven the Germans out of Tikhvin and have closed on Lyuban but the Germans still hold Shlisselburg and with it the land-route to Leningrad is still closed. The VVS-KBF and PVO regiments have fought heroically in the skies over Leningrad, preventing larger German terror raids and protecting the Red Banner Baltic fleet from being annihilated from the air. While doing so, the air regiments have taken heavily losses. For the upcoming counteroffensives, the VVS-KBF and PVO of Leningrad will have to be rebuilt.>

<GOF41WinterFiDb> <As of Feb 28, 1942 the Germans so far have failed to take Leningrad, but have put the city under a devastating siege and heavy air attacks. We have accomplished all goals of our war, but while 200.000 reservists are demobilized, a state of war still exists with the Soviet Union, even if actual combat is limited to air combat and static warfare in front of Leningrad. We will hold the front and wait how the general situation of the German-Russian war develops before entering peace negotiations on our terms with the Soviets.>


