<TunisiafFrBr> <After the defeat of May-June 1940 during the Battle of France, the Arme de l'Air (French Air Force) basically split into 2 groups: the Free French, a "small troop" continuing the fight together with the British and the Soviets, and the Vichy air force, subordinated to the new French government of Vichy, cooperating with the Germans. A large part of the Vichy armed forces were stationed in North Africa. Operation Torch took place on November 8th, 1942: US and British troops landed in Morocco and Algeria. The Vichy forces fought the Allies for 3 days and then surrendered. The local French resistance fighters in Algeria contributed significantly to this swift allied victory. Soon after, the French generals based in Algiers, the capital of Algeria, decided to cooperate with the Allies and to fight against Germany and Italy. \nOn the field, you are a member of the former Vichy air force, and as a pilot during the Battle of France, you have been quite ashamed by the previous situation; you are looking forward to continue the lost fight of 1940, against the Axis forces, and to liberate France from the Nazis. \nTo that effect, you will need a new aircraft to replace your ageing French plane from 1940. Thanks mainly to American understanding and cooperation, you will be satisfied: your squadron was just reequipped with new planes made in USA. The USA agreed to accept France as a beneficiary of the Lend-Lease system. \nUSAAF Colonel Harold Willis, a veteran of Escadrille Lafayette, the legendary squadron formed in 1916 with American volunteers who gave their life for France during World War I, made an effective lobbying to make this happen. You must make our American friends happy to help us, and show them that you deserve their valuable trust! \nChurchill also wanted Great Britain to participate to this French reequipment effort, and decided to contribute as well. As a first step in March 1943, the GC II/7 Nice is rearmed with Spitfires Mk Vc and becomes the RAF squadron 326.>
