<ArdennesfFrBr> <After the operations in Italy, Normandy, Provence and Eastern France, the German armies have evacuated almost all the French territory. However the Wehrmacht still resists in a few pockets, and we must continue to do our job, despite our heavy losses and the deadly Flak. \nSince 1943, a lot of progress has been made. The reconstruction of our Arme de l'Air is well underway, and the merger between the Free French and the former Vichy air force is now effective, thanks to the leadership of General Ren Bouscat and General Martial Valin, the former head of the Free French Air Force (FAFL). \nThis has not been an easy task. Some of our colleagues from the former FAFL still claim that we did not join the Allies early enough, and there are many tensions among ourselves. Nevertheless on the field, it is victory that matters, not politics. And you certainly give all what you have to reach this goal! \nWe also face a lot of delays: it is difficult for the Allies to deliver to us all the planes we need. Maybe our planning was too ambitious. There are also difficulties and delays in the training of our new pilots. Nevertheless, we carry on with determination and our new French air force is growing at a fast pace, unthinkable in 1942.>
<ArdennesfFrDb> <Well, fortunately spring has come. This 1944-45 winter has been terrible: one of the coldest in history. Under very difficult weather conditions, we had to counter a desperate but very aggressive German offensive in the Ardennes. Operation Bodenplatte has failed, and the German pilots are no longer as well trained as they used to be, but they have damned good new fighters, including jets. Furthermore, the Flak is as deadly as ever, and your squadron is exhausted. However, you still have to make more efforts, until we reach the final victory!>

